  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Tang Castle
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Human affairs rise in glory, then fade to dust—
    How can this fleeting life not pierce the heart?
    Who could have known that Heaven's melody
    Would drift to this sea-shore and cry?

    By water palaces I watched the flowers bloom,
    Before cool railings I faced the moon's glow.
    Those days of attending the former king are gone—
    Now both you and I weep tears without end.
  footnotes:
    - Tang Castle likely refers to a palace or fortress associated with the Tang Dynasty, serving as a meditation on imperial glory and its inevitable decline. Choi Chi-won was a Silla scholar-official (9th century) deeply influenced by Chinese culture.
    - The 'former king' alludes to a deceased ruler, suggesting the poet's lament over lost service and faded majesty.
